ce:section.ce:para:
The physicochemical properties of the nanocomposites were further systematically characterized by Raman, XPS, TGA, and XRD. Fig. 2
                        a displays the Raman spectra of N-CQDs, Yb-MnO2 and Yb-MnO2/N-CQDs. The strong band at 625 cm−1 in the Raman spectra of Yb-MnO2 and Yb-MnO2/N-CQDs stems from the symmetric Mn-O vibration. Furthermore, two characteristic Raman peaks of the N-CQDs located at 1340 cm−1 and 1600 cm−1 are discernible in the Raman spectra of Yb-MnO2/N-CQDs. These peaks correspond to the graphitic (G) and defective (D) bands, respectively. This observation confirms the successful combination of N-CQDs and Yb-MnO2 in forming the heterostructure. The XPS survey scan shows that the synthesized Yb-MnO2/N-CQDs composite primarily consists of Yb, Mn, N, C, and O elements (Fig. 2b), further confirming the successful construction of the heterogeneous structure. The atomic percentage of Yb, C, and N elements in the Yb-MnO2/N-CQDs nanocomposites calculated from XPS was 0.67 wt%, 27.46 wt% and 2.72 wt%, respectively (Table 1
                        ). The thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) curves are shown in Fig. 2c. The weight loss of MnO2, Yb-MnO2, and Yb-MnO2/N-CQDs from room temperature to 180 °C was 6.07%, 9.42%, and 8%, respectively, mainly due to the loss of the adsorbed water. The weight loss of samples from 180 °C to 280 °C was 1.30%, 1.56%, and 9.2%, respectively. The considerable weight loss observed in Yb-MnO2/N-CQDs within this temperature range can be attributed to the pyrolysis of N-CQDs, given that N-CQDs undergo pyrolysis under these conditions. The endothermic peaks observed around 400 °C in the samples may be derived from the structural transitions and self-decomposition process [42,43]. Based on the TGA, it can be roughly calculated that the percentage of N-CQDs in the composite is 7.7 wt%. The XRD spectra of the prepared materials were recorded for the crystal structure analysis (Fig. 2d). The N-CQDs show a diffraction peak centered at 25°, which can be assigned to the (002) diffraction patterns of graphitic carbon [44]. The pure MnO2 showed diffraction peaks of (110), (200), (310), (211), (411), and (521), which were in good agreement with the α-phase MnO2 (JCPDS 44–0141) [45]. For Yb-MnO2 material, no additional diffraction peaks corresponding to segregated crystalline phase of Yb2O3 were detected. This can be attributed to either the low Yb content or the effective dispersion of Yb within the nanostructure of MnO2. Additionally, a new diffraction peak located at 12.5° corresponding to the (001) plane of δ-MnO2 appears. Moreover, the diffraction peaks corresponding to α-MnO2 display broadening and a decrease in intensity. These observations indicate that the introduction of Yb3+ led to decreased material crystallinity and the formation of a mixed crystal phase. It is known that δ-MnO2 serves as the initially favored product in terms of kinetics and acts as the precursor of other MnO2 polymorphs [40]. Subsequently, the thermodynamically more favorable structures such as the α-, β-, and γ-phases emerge through the transformation of δ-MnO2. As discussed in the preceding paragraph, Yb3+ ions are likely to be inserted within the tunnel framework or the interspace of the material's layers rather than the MnO6 octahedral framework due to their large ionic radius. Thus, it is hypothesized that the incorporated Yb3+ ions into the interstitial spaces within the layers could stabilize the structural integrity of δ-MnO2 and hinder its transition into the α-phase, resulting in the formation of a mixed crystal phase. Importantly, an even greater broadening of the diffraction peak and a more pronounced reduction in peak intensity are observed in Yb-MnO2/N-CQDs nanocomposite. These observations likely stem from the further perturbation of the Yb-MnO2 crystallization process by the presence of N-CQDs.
